{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:25:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17025"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17025"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.1,0.03,0,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68288"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53745"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5126"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"9877"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68288"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with polyuria and polydipsia. She is diagnosed with central diabetes insipidus and prescribed desmopressin nasal spray.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of desmopressin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates V2 receptors to increase aquaporin-2 insertion","Increases sodium reabsorption in proximal tubules","Increases blood pressure via V1 receptor activation","Reduces glomerular filtration rate","Blocks aldosterone receptors in collecting ducts"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDesmopressin works by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating V2 receptors to increase aquaporin-2 insertion\u003C/strong\u003E in the collecting duct cells of the kidney. This increases water reabsorption and concentrates urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases sodium reabsorption in proximal tubules\u003C/strong\u003E: desmopressin does not directly affect sodium transport in the proximal tubule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases blood pressure via V1 receptor activation\u003C/strong\u003E: unlike vasopressin, desmopressin has minimal V1 receptor activity and therefore minimal effect on blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces glomerular filtration rate\u003C/strong\u003E: desmopressin does not significantly affect glomerular filtration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks aldosterone receptors in collecting ducts\u003C/strong\u003E: desmopressin does not interact with mineralocorticoid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen V2 receptors are activated, they trigger a signalling cascade that leads to insertion of aquaporin-2 water channels into the luminal membrane of collecting duct cells, allowing water to be reabsorbed down its concentration gradient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Desmopressin is a synthetic analogue of vasopressin that primarily acts on V2 receptors in the kidney collecting ducts.","Activation of V2 receptors increases water reabsorption by inserting aquaporin-2 channels into the luminal membrane.","Desmopressin has minimal vasopressor effects compared to vasopressin due to reduced V1 receptor binding."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17025"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T15:52:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T15:52:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68288"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (